04715nam a22006615i 9780674287433DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20222022mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806742874337 a10.4159/97806742874332doi  a(DE-B1597)634181  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aJK1726b.S325 2022eb 7aPHI0190002bisacsh04a320.9732221 aSandel, Michael J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDemocracy’s Discontent :bA New Edition for Our Perilous Times /cMichael J. Sandel. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (384 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface to the New Edition -- tPreface to the Original Edition -- tIntroduction to the New Edition: Democracy’s Peril -- t1 The Political Economy of Citizenship -- t2 Economics and Virtue in the Early Republic -- t3 Free Labor versus Wage Labor -- t4 Community, Self-Government, and Progressive Reform -- t5 Liberalism and the Keynesian Revolution -- t6 The Triumph and Travail of the Procedural Republic -- tConclusion: In Search of a Public Philosophy -- tEpilogue: What Went Wrong: Capitalism and Democracy since the 1990s -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA renowned political philosopher updates his classic book on the American political tradition to address the perils democracy confronts today.The 1990s were a heady time. The Cold War had ended, and America’s version of liberal capitalism seemed triumphant. And yet, amid the peace and prosperity, anxieties about the project of self-government could be glimpsed beneath the surface.So argued Michael Sandel, in his influential and widely debated book Democracy’s Discontent, published in 1996. The market faith was eroding the common life. A rising sense of disempowerment was likely to provoke backlash, he wrote, from those who would “shore up borders, harden the distinction between insiders and outsiders, and promise a politics to ‘take back our culture and take back our country,’ to ‘restore our sovereignty’ with a vengeance.”Now, a quarter century later, Sandel updates his classic work for an age when democracy’s discontent has hardened into a country divided against itself. In this new edition, he extends his account of America’s civic struggles from the 1990s to the present. He shows how Democrats and Republicans alike embraced a version of finance-driven globalization that created a society of winners and losers and fueled the toxic politics of our time.In a work celebrated when first published as “a remarkable fusion of philosophical and historical scholarship” (Alan Brinkley), Sandel recalls moments in the American past when the country found ways to hold economic power to democratic account. To reinvigorate democracy, Sandel argues in a stirring new epilogue, we need to reconfigure the economy and empower citizens as participants in a shared public life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aCitizenshipzUnited States. 0aCivil rightszUnited States. 0aDemocracyzUnited States. 0aLiberalismzUnited States. 0aPolitics, Practical. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311078579140uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/9780674287433?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674287433423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674287433/original  a978-3-11-078579-1  Harvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11S